{"title_page": "Substrate integrated waveguide", "text_new": "[[File:SIW sanstransparence.svg|thumb|Three-dimensional configuration of a classical substrate integrated waveguide. The propagating electromagnetic waves are confined inside the substrate because of the two metallic layers on the two faces of the substrate and the two rows of metallic vias connecting them.]]\n\nA '''Substrate integrated waveguide (SIW)''' (also known as '''post-wall waveguide''' or '''laminated waveguide''') is a synthetic [[Waveguide (radio frequency)|rectangular electromagnetic waveguide]] formed in a [[dielectric]] substrate by densely arraying metallized posts or [[Via (electronics)|via-hole]]s which connect the upper and lower metal plates of the substrate. The waveguide can be easily fabricated with low-cost mass-production using [[Through-hole technology|through-hole techniques]] where the post walls consists of [[via fence]]s. SIW is known to have similar guided wave and mode characteristics to conventional rectangular waveguide with equivalent [[guide wavelength]].\n\nSince the emergence of new communication technologies in the 1990s, there has been an increasing need for high-performance millimeter-wave systems. These need to be reliable, low-cost, compact, and compatible with high-frequencies. Unfortunately, above 10&nbsp;GHz, the well known [[microstrip]] and [[coplanar waveguide|coplanar lines]] technologies cannot be used because they have high insertion and radiation losses at these frequencies. The [[Waveguide (radio frequency)|rectangular waveguide]] topology can overcome these issues as it offers an excellent immunity against radiation losses and presents low insertion losses. But in their classical form, rectangular waveguide is not compatible with the miniaturization required by modern applications.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Ke Wu|last2=Desiandes|first2=D.|last3=Cassivi|first3=Y.|date=2003|title=The substrate integrated circuits - a new concept for high-frequency electronics and optoelectronics|url=http://ieeexplore.ieee.org/document/1246173/|journal=6th International Conference on Telecommunications in Modern Satellite, Cable and Broadcasting Service, 2003. TELSIKS 2003.|location=Serbia, Montenegro, Nis|publisher=IEEE|volume=1|pages=P\u2013III\u2013P-X|doi=10.1109/TELSKS.2003.1246173|isbn=978-0-7803-7963-3}}</ref>\n\nThe concept of SIW was developed in the early 2000s by [[Ke Wu]] to reconcile those requirements.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Deslandes|first=D.|last2=Ke Wu|date=2001|title=Integrated transition of coplanar to rectangular waveguides|url=http://ieeexplore.ieee.org/document/966971/|journal=2001 IEEE MTT-S International Microwave Sympsoium Digest (Cat. No.01CH37157)|location=Phoenix, AZ, USA|publisher=IEEE|volume=2|pages=619\u2013622|doi=10.1109/MWSYM.2001.966971|isbn=978-0-7803-6538-4}}</ref> The authors presented a platform for integrating all the components of a microwave circuit inside a single substrate, with a rectangular cross-section. Using a single substrate guarantees a limited volume and a simplicity of manufacture, while the rectangular cross-section of the line provides the advantages of the waveguide topology in terms of losses.\n\n== Principles of SIW ==\n\n[[File:SIW horizontal.png|alt=Horizontal cross-section of a classical substrate integrated waveguide.|thumb|Horizontal cross-section of a classical substrate integrated waveguide. The propagating electromagnetic waves are confined inside the substrate because of the two metallic layers on the two faces of the substrate and the two rows of metallic vias connecting them. The center-to-center distance of two successive vias is <math display=\"inline\">s</math>, their diameter is <math display=\"inline\">d</math> and the center-to-center distance between the two rows of vias is <math display=\"inline\">a</math>. The effective width <math display=\"inline\">a_e</math>, computed from <math display=\"inline\">a</math>, <math display=\"inline\">d</math> and <math display=\"inline\">s</math> is also presented.]]\n\n=== Geometry ===\n\nA classical SIW is composed of a thin dielectric substrate covered on both faces by a metallic layer. The substrate embeds two parallel rows of metallic [[via (electronics)|via-holes]] delimiting the wave propagation area. The organization of the vias and the geometric parameters are described in the attached figure.\n\nThe width of a SIW is the distance <math>a</math> between its two vias rows, which is defined from center-to-center. An [[#Effective width|effective width]] <math>a_e</math> may be used to characterize more precisely the wave propagation. The distance between two successive vias of the same row is <math>s</math>, and the vias diameter is denoted by <math>d</math>.\n\n=== Transverse magnetic propagation modes ===\n\nIn classical rectangular waveguide, the general formulation of propagation involves a superposition of [[Transverse mode|transverse electric]] (TE) and [[Transverse mode|transverse magnetic]] (TM) modes. Each of these is associated with particular fields and currents. In the case of TM modes, the current in the vertical walls is longitudinal, i.e. parallel to the propagation axis, usually denoted as <math>z</math>. Then, given the vertical geometry of the vias, it is impossible for such modes to appear in SIW's: the electrical current cannot propagate from via to via. Only TE modes are able to propagate through SIW.\n\nEach mode appears above a precise cut-off frequency determined by the waveguide dimensions and the filling medium. For TM modes, decreasing the waveguide thickness (usually denoted as <math>b</math>) increases the cut-off frequency with <math>1/b</math>. In the case of SIW, the thickness is so low that the cut-off frequency of TM modes is much higher than the dominant mode.\n\n=== Effective width ===\n\nOne of the objectives of the SIW geometry is to reproduce the characteristic propagation modes of rectangular waveguides inside a thin template. The width <math>a</math> of the waveguide is an essential parameter of those modes. In the typical SIW geometry, <math>a</math> is the distance between the two vias rows from center-to-center (see figure). Due to the vias geometry, this distance cannot be utilized directly; because of the space between successive vias and their circular shape, the signal inside the guide does not behave exactly as it would in a perfectly rectangular waveguide of the same width.\n\nTo apply waveguide theory to SIWs, an effective width <math>a_\\text{eff}</math>can be used. Its takes into account the shape of the vias and the space in-between. Its value lies between <math>a + d</math> and <math>a - d</math>.\n\nA common simple definition is<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Bozzi|first=M.|last2=Georgiadis|first2=A.|last3=Wu|first3=K.|date=2011|title=Review of substrate-integrated waveguide circuits and antennas|url=https://digital-library.theiet.org/content/journals/10.1049/iet-map.2010.0463|journal=IET Microwaves, Antennas & Propagation|language=en|volume=5|issue=8|pages=909|doi=10.1049/iet-map.2010.0463}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Cassivi|first=Y.|last2=Perregrini|first2=L.|last3=Arcioni|first3=P.|last4=Bressan|first4=M.|last5=Wu|first5=K.|last6=Conciauro|first6=G.|date=September 2002|title=Dispersion characteristics of substrate integrated rectangular waveguide|url=http://ieeexplore.ieee.org/document/1031925/|journal=IEEE Microwave and Wireless Components Letters|volume=12|issue=9|pages=333\u2013335|doi=10.1109/LMWC.2002.803188|issn=1531-1309}}</ref>\n\n<math>a_\\text{eff} = a - \\frac{d^2}{0.95 s}</math>\n\nand a more refined definition used for large values of <math>d/a</math> is,<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|last=Feng Xu|last2=Ke Wu|date=January 2005|title=Guided-wave and leakage characteristics of substrate integrated waveguide|url=http://ieeexplore.ieee.org/document/1381676/|journal=IEEE Transactions on Microwave Theory and Techniques|volume=53|issue=1|pages=66\u201373|doi=10.1109/TMTT.2004.839303|issn=0018-9480}}</ref><br /><math>a_\\text{eff} = a - 1.08 \\frac{d^2}{s} + 0.1 \\frac{d^2}{a}.</math>\n\nUsing this effective width, the propagation constant of a SIW will be similar to that of a classical rectangular waveguide whose width is <math>a_\\text{eff}</math>. The formulas given above are empirical: they were established comparing the dispersion characteristics of different SIWs to those of rectangular waveguide filled with the same dielectric material.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Transitions ==\n\nSIWs are promising structures that can be used in complex microwave systems as interconnects, filters, etc. However, a problem may arise: the connection of the SIWs with other kinds of [[Transmission line|transmission lines (TL)]], mainly [[microstrip]], [[Coplanar waveguide|coplanar]] and [[coaxial cable]]. The goal of such transitions between two different topologies of TL is to excite the correct transmission mode in the SIW cavity with the minimum loss of power and on the broadest possible frequency range.\n\nRapidly after the presentation of the concept of SIW by [[Ke Wu]], two different transitions were mainly used<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\" />. First, the tapered transition allowing to convert a microstrip line into a SIW and secondly a transition between a coplanar line and a SIW (see attached figure). The tapered transition from microstrip to SIW is useful for thin substrates. In this case, the radiation losses associated with microstrip lines are not too significant. This transition is massively used and different optimizing process have been proposed.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rayas-Sanchez|first=Jose E.|last2=Gutierrez-Ayala|first2=Vladimir|date=2008|title=A general EM-based design procedure for single-layer substrate integrated waveguide interconnects with microstrip transitions|url=https://ieeexplore.ieee.org/document/4632999/|journal=2008 IEEE MTT-S International Microwave Symposium Digest|pages=983\u2013986|doi=10.1109/MWSYM.2008.4632999}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Deslandes|first=Dominic|date=2010|title=Design equations for tapered microstrip-to-Substrate Integrated Waveguide transitions|url=https://ieeexplore.ieee.org/document/5517884/|journal=2010 IEEE MTT-S International Microwave Symposium|pages=704\u2013707|doi=10.1109/MWSYM.2010.5517884}}</ref> But this is not applicable to thick substrates where leakages are important. In that situation, a coplanar excitation of the SIW is recommended. The drawback of the coplanar transition is the narrower bandwidth.\n\nThese two kinds of transitions involve lines that are embedded in the same substrate, which is not the case for coaxial lines. There exists no direct transition between a coaxial line and a SIW: an other planar line have to be used to convert properly the coaxial TEM propagation modes to the TE modes in SIW.\n\nSeveral studies have been carried out to optimize the transition between topologies without being able to determine a universal rule making it possible to draw the absolute transition. The architecture, the frequency range, the used materials, etc. are examples of parameters that make specific the design procedure.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bozzi|first=M.|last2=Georgiadis|first2=A.|last3=Wu|first3=K.|date=2011|title=Review of substrate-integrated waveguide circuits and antennas|url=https://digital-library.theiet.org/content/journals/10.1049/iet-map.2010.0463|journal=IET Microwaves, Antennas & Propagation|language=en|volume=5|issue=8|pages=909|doi=10.1049/iet-map.2010.0463}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Chen|first=Xiao-Ping|last2=Wu|first2=Ke|date=2009|title=Low-loss ultra-wideband transition between conductor-backed coplanar waveguide and substrate integrated waveguide|url=https://ieeexplore.ieee.org/document/5165705/|journal=2009 IEEE MTT-S International Microwave Symposium Digest|pages=349\u2013352|doi=10.1109/MWSYM.2009.5165705}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lee|first=Sunho|last2=Jung|first2=Sangwoon|last3=Lee|first3=Hai-Young|date=2008|title=Ultra-Wideband CPW-to-Substrate Integrated Waveguide Transition Using an Elevated-CPW Section|url=http://ieeexplore.ieee.org/document/4666756/|journal=IEEE Microwave and Wireless Components Letters|volume=18|issue=11|pages=746\u2013748|doi=10.1109/LMWC.2008.2005230|issn=1531-1309}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Taringou|first=Farzaneh|last2=Bornemann|first2=Jens|date=2011|title=New substrate-integrated to coplanar waveguide transition|url=https://ieeexplore.ieee.org/abstract/document/6101767/|journal=2011 41st European Microwave Conference|pages=428\u2013431|doi=10.23919/EuMC.2011.6101767}}</ref>\n\n{{multiple image\n| align    = center   \n| direction = horizontal\n| image1   = SIW tapered transition.svg\n| caption1 = Transition from microstrip to SIW\n| width1   = 200\n| image2   = SIW transition CPWG.svg\n| caption2 = Transition from a coplanar line to a SIW\n| width2   = 200\n| footer   = Examples of transitions from coplanar and microstrip lines to SIW. In red : the vias. In grey : the top metallic layer.\n}}<br />\n\n== Losses in SIW ==\nThe [[propagation constant]] of a transmission line is often decomposed as follow :\n\n<math display=\"block\">\\gamma = \\alpha + j \\beta</math>\n\nand the oscillating [[Electric field|electric]] and [[Magnetic field|magnetic]] fields in the guide have the form<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|last=Pozar, David M.|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/884711361|title=Microwave engineering|isbn=978-81-265-4190-4|oclc=884711361}}</ref><math display=\"block\">\\begin{align}\nH_{x,y,z}(x,y,z) &= h_{x,y,z} e^{- \\gamma z} = h_{x,y,z} e^{- \\alpha z} e^{- j \\beta z} \\\\\nE_{x,y,z}(x,y,z) &= e_{x,y,z} e^{- \\gamma z} = e_{x,y,z} e^{- \\alpha z} e^{- j \\beta z}\n\\end{align}</math>It is then clear that, while the imaginary part of <math>\\gamma</math> stands for the propagating component, the real component <math>\\alpha</math> describes the loss of intensity during the propagation. This loss is generated by different phenomena and each of them is represented by a term <math>\\alpha</math>. The most common terms are the following:<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.microwaves101.com/encyclopedias/waveguide-loss|title=Microwaves101 {{!}} Waveguide Loss|website=www.microwaves101.com|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n*<math>\\alpha_C</math> : the loss due to the external metal conductivity\n*<math>\\alpha_D\n</math> : the loss due to loss tangent of the dielectric medium filling the waveguide\n*<math>\\alpha_G</math> : the loss due to conductivity of the dielectric medium filling the waveguide\n*<math>\\alpha_R</math> : the loss due to radiation.\n\nThis decomposition is valid for all kind of [[Transmission line|transmission lines]]. However, for [[Rectangular waveguide|rectangular waveguides]], the attenuation due to radiations and substrate [[Electrical conductivity|conductivity]] is negligible. Indeed, usually, the substrate is an insulator such that <math>\\alpha_G \\simeq 0</math>. In the same way, if the wall thickness is much thicker than the skin depth of the signal, no radiation will appear. This is in fact one of the advantages of closed waveguides compared to open lines such as microstrips.\n\nThe SIWs show comparable or lower losses compared the other traditional planar structures like microstrip or coplanar lines especially at high frequencies.<ref name=\":4\" /> If the substrate is thick enough, the losses are dominated by the dielectric behavior of the substrate.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n=== Attenuation due to conduction currents ===\nPart of the signal attenuation is due to the [[Current density|surface current density]] flowing through the metallic walls of the waveguide. These currents are induced by the propagating [[Electromagnetic field|electromagnetic fields]]. These losses may also be named ohmic losses for obvious reasons. They are linked to the finite conductivity of the metals: the better the conduction, the lower the losses. The power lost per unit length <math>P_l</math> can be calculated by integrating the current densities <math>J_s</math> on a path <math>C</math> enclosing the waveguide walls : <ref name=\":3\" /> \n\n<math display=\"block\">P_l = \\frac{1}{2} R_s \\int_C |{J_s}|^2 dl.</math>\n\nIt can be shown that in a classical rectangular waveguide, the attenuation of the dominant mode <math>\\text{TE}_{10}</math> due to conduction currents is given, in [[Neper|Nepers]] per [[Metre|meter]], by<math display=\"block\" id=\"alpha_c_expression\">\\alpha_C = \\frac{R_s}{a^3 b \\beta k \\eta}  \\left( 2 b \\pi^2 + a^3 k^2 \\right) =  \\frac{R_s}{\\beta k \\eta} \\left( \\frac{2 \\pi^2}{a^3 } + \\frac{k^2}{b} \\right)</math>where\n\n* <math>a</math> is the width of the waveguide\n* <math>b</math> its height\n* <math>\\eta = \\sqrt{\\mu / \\epsilon}</math> the [[wave impedance]] \n* <math>k = \\omega \\sqrt{\\mu \\epsilon}</math> the [[wave vector]]\n* <math>\\delta = 1 / \\sqrt{\\pi f \\mu \\sigma}</math> the [[Skin Depth|skin depth]] in the conductor \n* <math>R_s = \\frac{1}{\\delta \\sigma} = \\sqrt{\\frac{\\omega \\mu}{2 \\sigma}}</math> is the [[sheet resistance]] (of surface impedance).\n\nIt is noticeable that <math>\\alpha_C</math> is directly linked to the substrate thickness <math>b</math>: the thinner the substrate, the higher the conduction losses. This can be explained keeping in mind that this ohmic losses are determined by integrating the current density on a path enclosing the waveguide walls. \n\nOn the top and bottom horizontal metallic plates, the current is scaled with <math>1/b</math>, due to the modification of the field intensity on these plates: when <math>b</math> increases, the field intensity decreases as well as the currents. In the vertical walls, this variation of <math>J_s^2</math> is compensated by the lengthening of the integration path <math>C</math>. As a result, the contribution of the vertical vias to the conductor losses is unchanged with <math>b</math>.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite journal|last=Bozzi|first=M.|last2=Perregrini|first2=L.|last3=Ke Wu|date=2008|title=Modeling of Conductor, Dielectric, and Radiation Losses in Substrate Integrated Waveguide by the Boundary Integral-Resonant Mode Expansion Method|url=http://ieeexplore.ieee.org/document/4682637/|journal=IEEE Transactions on Microwave Theory and Techniques|volume=56|issue=12|pages=3153\u20133161|doi=10.1109/TMTT.2008.2007140|issn=0018-9480}}</ref> That is the reason why there is two terms in the expression of <math>\\alpha_C</math>: the first is independent of <math>b</math> while the second one varies with <math>1/b</math>.\n\nAnother key point of the conduction losses experienced by the SIWs is linked to the [[Surface roughness|roughness]] of the surfaces that may appear due to the synthesis processes. This roughness decreases the effective conductivity of the metallic walls and subsequently increases the losses. This observation is of crucial importance for the design of SIWs as they are integrated on very thin substrates. In this case, the contribution of the conduction losses on the global attenuation is predominant.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lomakin|first=Konstantin|last2=Gold|first2=Gerald|last3=Helmreich|first3=Klaus|date=2018|title=Analytical Waveguide Model Precisely Predicting Loss and Delay Including Surface Roughness|url=https://ieeexplore.ieee.org/document/8356729/|journal=IEEE Transactions on Microwave Theory and Techniques|volume=66|issue=6|pages=2649\u20132662|doi=10.1109/TMTT.2018.2827383|issn=0018-9480}}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite thesis|title=Nanowire-based microwave devices in substrate integrated waveguide topology using a laser-assisted fabrication process|url=https://dial.uclouvain.be/pr/boreal/object/boreal:222909|publisher=UCL - Universit\u00e9 Catholique de Louvain|date=2019|language=en|first=Vivien|last=Van Kerckhoven}}</ref>\n\n=== Attenuation due to dielectric substrate ===\nThe attenuation due the [[dielectric]] behavior of the filling medium can be determined directly from the [[propagation constant]].<ref name=\":3\" /> Indeed, it can be proven that, making use of a [[Taylor expansion]] of the function <math display=\"inline\">\\sqrt{a^2 + x^2}</math> for <math display=\"inline\">x \\ll a</math>, the propagation constant is<math display=\"block\" id=\"alpha_c_expression\">\\gamma = \\alpha_D + j \\beta \\simeq \\frac{k^2 \\tan{\\delta}}{2 \\beta} + j\\beta</math>where <math>\\tan \\delta</math> is the [[loss tangent]] of the dielectric substrate. This approximation is correct if <math display=\"inline\">\\tan{\\delta} \\ll 1</math> which is usually the case in microwave electronics. At 10 GHz, <math display=\"inline\" id=\"alpha_c_expression\">\\tan{\\delta} = 0</math> in air, <math>1.5 \\times 10^{-4}</math> in Teflon and <math>1 \\times 10^{-4}</math>1 in bulk alumina. Then, the following identification can be made:<math display=\"block\" id=\"alpha_c_expression\">\\alpha_D = \\frac{k^2 \\tan{\\delta}}{2 \\beta}.</math>This relation is correct for both electrical and magnetic transverse modes.\n\n\nThe dielectric losses <math display=\"inline\" id=\"alpha_c_expression\">\\alpha_D</math> depend only on the substrate and not on the geometry: unlike the conduction losses, <math display=\"inline\" id=\"alpha_c_expression\">\\alpha_D</math> is not influenced by the substrate thickness. It transpires that the only way to reduce <math display=\"inline\" id=\"alpha_c_expression\">\\alpha_D</math> consists in choosing a template with better dielectric properties: the lower the loss tangent <math display=\"inline\" id=\"alpha_c_expression\">\\tan{\\delta}</math>, the lower the attenuation. \n\n=== Attenuation due to radiation ===\nBecause the vertical walls of the SIW are not continuous, radiation leakages may flow between the vias. These leakages can significantly affect the global transmission quality if the vias geometry is not chosen carefully. Some studies have been conducted to describe, predict and reduce the radiation losses. They have resulted in some simple geometric rules that have to be satisfied in order to reduce the radiation losses. <ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":7\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bozzi|first=Maurizio|last2=Pasian|first2=Marco|last3=Perregrini|first3=Luca|last4=Wu|first4=Ke|date=2009-10|title=On the losses in substrate-integrated waveguides and cavities|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/product/identifier/S1759078709990493/type/journal_article|journal=International Journal of Microwave and Wireless Technologies|language=en|volume=1|issue=5|pages=395\u2013401|doi=10.1017/S1759078709990493|issn=1759-0787}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Che|first=Wenquan|last2=Wang|first2=Dapeng|last3=Deng|first3=Kuan|last4=Chow|first4=Y. L.|date=2007-10|title=Leakage and ohmic losses investigation in substrate-integrated waveguide: SUBSTRATE-INTEGRATED WAVEGUIDE|url=http://doi.wiley.com/10.1029/2007RS003621|journal=Radio Science|language=en|volume=42|issue=5|pages=n/a\u2013n/a|doi=10.1029/2007RS003621}}</ref>\n\nThe geometric parameters of interest are the diameter <math display=\"inline\">d</math>, the spacing <math>s</math> and the center-to-center distance between the vias <math>a</math>. They must be tuned in such a way to approximate the behavior of a continuous metallic wall: the spacing of the vias has to remain small compared to their diameter, while the diameter must be small compared to the waveguide width (or waveguide wavelength). To keep the radiation losses reasonably small, the recommended values are<math display=\"block\">s \\leq 2 d ~~~~~~ \\textrm{and} ~~~~~~ d \\leq \\frac{a}{5}.</math>For a specific traveling mode, the leakages decrease with the increasing frequency and are maximal at the cut-off frequency of the mode. The radiation leakage factor <math>\\alpha_R</math> is independent of the substrate properties and independent of the height of the guide.\n\n==See also==\n* {{section link|Planar transmission line|Substrate integrated waveguide}}, also\n** {{section link|Planar transmission line|Transitions}}\n** {{section link|Planar transmission line|Circuit gallery}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.microwaves101.com/encyclopedias/substrate-integrated-waveguide Substrate Integrated Waveguide], at microwave101.com\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Substrate_Integrated_Waveguide}}\n[[Category:Planar transmission lines]]\n[[Category:Electronic design]]\n[[Category:Microwave technology]]\n[[Category:Electronics manufacturing]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:SIW sanstransparence.svg|thumb|Three-dimensional configuration of a classical substrate integrated waveguide. The propagating electromagnetic waves are confined inside the substrate because of the two metallic layers on the two faces of the substrate and the two rows of metallic vias connecting them.]]\n\nA '''Substrate integrated waveguide (SIW)''' (also known as '''post-wall waveguide''' or '''laminated waveguide''') is a synthetic [[Waveguide (radio frequency)|rectangular electromagnetic waveguide]] formed in a [[dielectric]] substrate by densely arraying metallized posts or [[Via (electronics)|via-hole]]s which connect the upper and lower metal plates of the substrate. The waveguide can be easily fabricated with low-cost mass-production using [[Through-hole technology|through-hole techniques]] where the post walls consists of [[via fence]]s. SIW is known to have similar guided wave and mode characteristics to conventional rectangular waveguide with equivalent [[guide wavelength]].\n\nSince the emergence of new communication technologies in the 1990s, there has been an increasing need for high-performance millimeter-wave systems. These need to be reliable, low-cost, compact, and compatible with high-frequencies. Unfortunately, above 10&nbsp;GHz, the well known [[microstrip]] and [[coplanar waveguide|coplanar lines]] technologies cannot be used because they have high insertion and radiation losses at these frequencies. The [[Waveguide (radio frequency)|rectangular waveguide]] topology can overcome these issues as it offers an excellent immunity against radiation losses and presents low insertion losses. But in their classical form, rectangular waveguide is not compatible with the miniaturization required by modern applications.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Ke Wu|last2=Desiandes|first2=D.|last3=Cassivi|first3=Y.|date=2003|title=The substrate integrated circuits - a new concept for high-frequency electronics and optoelectronics|url=http://ieeexplore.ieee.org/document/1246173/|journal=6th International Conference on Telecommunications in Modern Satellite, Cable and Broadcasting Service, 2003. TELSIKS 2003.|location=Serbia, Montenegro, Nis|publisher=IEEE|volume=1|pages=P\u2013III\u2013P-X|doi=10.1109/TELSKS.2003.1246173|isbn=978-0-7803-7963-3}}</ref>\n\nThe concept of SIW was developed in the early 2000s by [[Ke Wu]] to reconcile those requirements.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Deslandes|first=D.|last2=Ke Wu|date=2001|title=Integrated transition of coplanar to rectangular waveguides|url=http://ieeexplore.ieee.org/document/966971/|journal=2001 IEEE MTT-S International Microwave Sympsoium Digest (Cat. No.01CH37157)|location=Phoenix, AZ, USA|publisher=IEEE|volume=2|pages=619\u2013622|doi=10.1109/MWSYM.2001.966971|isbn=978-0-7803-6538-4}}</ref> The authors presented a platform for integrating all the components of a microwave circuit inside a single substrate, with a rectangular cross-section. Using a single substrate guarantees a limited volume and a simplicity of manufacture, while the rectangular cross-section of the line provides the advantages of the waveguide topology in terms of losses.\n\n== Principles of SIW ==\n\n[[File:SIW horizontal.png|alt=Horizontal cross-section of a classical substrate integrated waveguide.|thumb|Horizontal cross-section of a classical substrate integrated waveguide. The propagating electromagnetic waves are confined inside the substrate because of the two metallic layers on the two faces of the substrate and the two rows of metallic vias connecting them. The center-to-center distance of two successive vias is <math>s</math>, their diameter is <math>d</math> and the center-to-center distance between the two rows of vias is <math>a</math>. The effective width <math>a_e</math>, computed from <math>a</math>, <math>d</math> and <math>s</math>,with is also presented.]]\n\n=== Geometry ===\n\nA classical SIW is composed of a thin dielectric substrate covered on both faces by a metallic layer. The substrate embeds two parallel rows of metallic [[via (electronics)|via-holes]] delimiting the wave propagation area. The organization of the vias and the geometric parameters are described in the attached figure.\n\nThe width of a SIW is the distance <math>a</math> between its two vias rows, which is defined from center-to-center. An [[#Effective width|effective width]] <math>a_e</math> may be used to characterize more precisely the wave propagation. The distance between two successive vias of the same row is <math>s</math>, and the vias diameter is denoted by <math>d</math>.\n\n=== Transverse magnetic propagation modes ===\n\nIn classical rectangular waveguide, the general formulation of propagation involves a superposition of [[Transverse mode|transverse electric]] (TE) and [[Transverse mode|transverse magnetic]] (TM) modes. Each of these is associated with particular fields and currents. In the case of TM modes, the current in the vertical walls is longitudinal, i.e. parallel to the propagation axis, usually denoted as <math>z</math>. Then, given the vertical geometry of the vias, it is impossible for such modes to appear in SIW's: the electrical current cannot propagate from via to via. Only TE modes are able to propagate through SIW.\n\nEach mode appears above a precise cut-off frequency determined by the waveguide dimensions and the filling medium. For TM modes, decreasing the waveguide thickness (usually denoted as <math>b</math>) increases the cut-off frequency with <math>1/b</math>. In the case of SIW, the thickness is so low that the cut-off frequency of TM modes is much higher than the dominant mode.\n\n=== Effective width ===\n\nOne of the objectives of the SIW geometry is to reproduce the characteristic propagation modes of rectangular waveguides inside a thin template. The width <math>a</math> of the waveguide is an essential parameter of those modes. In the typical SIW geometry, <math>a</math> is the distance between the two vias rows from center-to-center (see figure). Due to the vias geometry, this distance cannot be utilized directly; because of the space between successive vias and their circular shape, the signal inside the guide does not behave exactly as it would in a perfectly rectangular waveguide of the same width.\n\nTo apply waveguide theory to SIWs, an effective width <math>a_\\text{eff}</math>can be used. Its takes into account the shape of the vias and the space in-between. Its value lies between <math>a + d</math> and <math>a - d</math>.\n\nA common simple definition is<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Bozzi|first=M.|last2=Georgiadis|first2=A.|last3=Wu|first3=K.|date=2011|title=Review of substrate-integrated waveguide circuits and antennas|url=https://digital-library.theiet.org/content/journals/10.1049/iet-map.2010.0463|journal=IET Microwaves, Antennas & Propagation|language=en|volume=5|issue=8|pages=909|doi=10.1049/iet-map.2010.0463}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Cassivi|first=Y.|last2=Perregrini|first2=L.|last3=Arcioni|first3=P.|last4=Bressan|first4=M.|last5=Wu|first5=K.|last6=Conciauro|first6=G.|date=September 2002|title=Dispersion characteristics of substrate integrated rectangular waveguide|url=http://ieeexplore.ieee.org/document/1031925/|journal=IEEE Microwave and Wireless Components Letters|volume=12|issue=9|pages=333\u2013335|doi=10.1109/LMWC.2002.803188|issn=1531-1309}}</ref>\n\n<math>a_\\text{eff} = a - \\frac{d^2}{0.95 s}</math>\n\nand a more refined definition used for large values of <math>d/a</math> is,<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|last=Feng Xu|last2=Ke Wu|date=January 2005|title=Guided-wave and leakage characteristics of substrate integrated waveguide|url=http://ieeexplore.ieee.org/document/1381676/|journal=IEEE Transactions on Microwave Theory and Techniques|volume=53|issue=1|pages=66\u201373|doi=10.1109/TMTT.2004.839303|issn=0018-9480}}</ref><br /><math>a_\\text{eff} = a - 1.08 \\frac{d^2}{s} + 0.1 \\frac{d^2}{a}.</math>\n\nUsing this effective width, the propagation constant of a SIW will be similar to that of a classical rectangular waveguide whose width is <math>a_\\text{eff}</math>. The formulas given above are empirical: they were established comparing the dispersion characteristics of different SIWs to those of rectangular waveguide filled with the same dielectric material.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Transitions ==\n\nSIWs are promising structures that can be used in complex microwave systems as interconnects, filters, etc. However, a problem may arise: the connection of the SIWs with other kinds of [[Transmission line|transmission lines (TL)]], mainly [[microstrip]], [[Coplanar waveguide|coplanar]] and [[coaxial cable]]. The goal of such transitions between two different topologies of TL is to excite the correct transmission mode in the SIW cavity with the minimum loss of power and on the broadest possible frequency range.\n\nRapidly after the presentation of the concept of SIW by [[Ke Wu]], two different transitions were mainly used<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\" />. First, the tapered transition allowing to convert a microstrip line into a SIW and secondly a transition between a coplanar line and a SIW (see attached figure). The tapered transition from microstrip to SIW is useful for thin substrates. In this case, the radiation losses associated with microstrip lines are not too significant. This transition is massively used and different optimizing process have been proposed.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rayas-Sanchez|first=Jose E.|last2=Gutierrez-Ayala|first2=Vladimir|date=2008|title=A general EM-based design procedure for single-layer substrate integrated waveguide interconnects with microstrip transitions|url=https://ieeexplore.ieee.org/document/4632999/|journal=2008 IEEE MTT-S International Microwave Symposium Digest|pages=983\u2013986|doi=10.1109/MWSYM.2008.4632999}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Deslandes|first=Dominic|date=2010|title=Design equations for tapered microstrip-to-Substrate Integrated Waveguide transitions|url=https://ieeexplore.ieee.org/document/5517884/|journal=2010 IEEE MTT-S International Microwave Symposium|pages=704\u2013707|doi=10.1109/MWSYM.2010.5517884}}</ref> But this is not applicable to thick substrates where leakages are important. In that situation, a coplanar excitation of the SIW is recommended. The drawback of the coplanar transition is the narrower bandwidth.\n\nThese two kinds of transitions involve lines that are embedded in the same substrate, which is not the case for coaxial lines. There exists no direct transition between a coaxial line and a SIW: an other planar line have to be used to convert properly the coaxial TEM propagation modes to the TE modes in SIW.\n\nSeveral studies have been carried out to optimize the transition between topologies without being able to determine a universal rule making it possible to draw the absolute transition. The architecture, the frequency range, the used materials, etc. are examples of parameters that make specific the design procedure.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bozzi|first=M.|last2=Georgiadis|first2=A.|last3=Wu|first3=K.|date=2011|title=Review of substrate-integrated waveguide circuits and antennas|url=https://digital-library.theiet.org/content/journals/10.1049/iet-map.2010.0463|journal=IET Microwaves, Antennas & Propagation|language=en|volume=5|issue=8|pages=909|doi=10.1049/iet-map.2010.0463}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Chen|first=Xiao-Ping|last2=Wu|first2=Ke|date=2009|title=Low-loss ultra-wideband transition between conductor-backed coplanar waveguide and substrate integrated waveguide|url=https://ieeexplore.ieee.org/document/5165705/|journal=2009 IEEE MTT-S International Microwave Symposium Digest|pages=349\u2013352|doi=10.1109/MWSYM.2009.5165705}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lee|first=Sunho|last2=Jung|first2=Sangwoon|last3=Lee|first3=Hai-Young|date=2008|title=Ultra-Wideband CPW-to-Substrate Integrated Waveguide Transition Using an Elevated-CPW Section|url=http://ieeexplore.ieee.org/document/4666756/|journal=IEEE Microwave and Wireless Components Letters|volume=18|issue=11|pages=746\u2013748|doi=10.1109/LMWC.2008.2005230|issn=1531-1309}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Taringou|first=Farzaneh|last2=Bornemann|first2=Jens|date=2011|title=New substrate-integrated to coplanar waveguide transition|url=https://ieeexplore.ieee.org/abstract/document/6101767/|journal=2011 41st European Microwave Conference|pages=428\u2013431|doi=10.23919/EuMC.2011.6101767}}</ref>\n\n{{multiple image\n| align    = center   \n| direction = horizontal\n| image1   = SIW tapered transition.svg\n| caption1 = Transition from microstrip to SIW\n| width1   = 200\n| image2   = SIW transition CPWG.svg\n| caption2 = Transition from a coplanar line to a SIW\n| width2   = 200\n| footer   = Examples of transitions from coplanar and microstrip lines to SIW. In red : the vias. In grey : the top metallic layer.\n}}<br />\n\n== Losses in SIW ==\nThe [[propagation constant]] of a transmission line is often decomposed as follow :\n\n<math display=\"block\">\\gamma = \\alpha + j \\beta</math>\n\nand the oscillating [[Electric field|electric]] and [[Magnetic field|magnetic]] fields in the guide have the form<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|last=Pozar, David M.|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/884711361|title=Microwave engineering|isbn=978-81-265-4190-4|oclc=884711361}}</ref><math display=\"block\">\\begin{align}\nH_{x,y,z}(x,y,z) &= h_{x,y,z} e^{- \\gamma z} = h_{x,y,z} e^{- \\alpha z} e^{- j \\beta z} \\\\\nE_{x,y,z}(x,y,z) &= e_{x,y,z} e^{- \\gamma z} = e_{x,y,z} e^{- \\alpha z} e^{- j \\beta z}\n\\end{align}</math>It is then clear that, while the imaginary part of <math>\\gamma</math> stands for the propagating component, the real component <math>\\alpha</math> describes the loss of intensity during the propagation. This loss is generated by different phenomena and each of them is represented by a term <math>\\alpha</math>. The most common terms are the following:<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.microwaves101.com/encyclopedias/waveguide-loss|title=Microwaves101 {{!}} Waveguide Loss|website=www.microwaves101.com|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n*<math>\\alpha_C</math> : the loss due to the external metal conductivity\n*<math>\\alpha_D\n</math> : the loss due to loss tangent of the dielectric medium filling the waveguide\n*<math>\\alpha_G</math> : the loss due to conductivity of the dielectric medium filling the waveguide\n*<math>\\alpha_R</math> : the loss due to radiation.\n\nThis decomposition is valid for all kind of [[Transmission line|transmission lines]]. However, for [[Rectangular waveguide|rectangular waveguides]], the attenuation due to radiations and substrate [[Electrical conductivity|conductivity]] is negligible. Indeed, usually, the substrate is an insulator such that <math>\\alpha_G \\simeq 0</math>. In the same way, if the wall thickness is much thicker than the skin depth of the signal, no radiation will appear. This is in fact one of the advantages of closed waveguides compared to open lines such as microstrips.\n\nThe SIWs show comparable or lower losses compared the other traditional planar structures like microstrip or coplanar lines especially at high frequencies.<ref name=\":4\" /> If the substrate is thick enough, the losses are dominated by the dielectric behavior of the substrate.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n=== Attenuation due to conduction currents ===\nPart of the signal attenuation is due to the [[Current density|surface current density]] flowing through the metallic walls of the waveguide. These currents are induced by the propagating [[Electromagnetic field|electromagnetic fields]]. These losses may also be named ohmic losses for obvious reasons. They are linked to the finite conductivity of the metals: the better the conduction, the lower the losses. The power lost per unit length <math>P_l</math> can be calculated by integrating the current densities <math>J_s</math> on a path <math>C</math> enclosing the waveguide walls : <ref name=\":3\" /> \n\n<math display=\"block\">P_l = \\frac{1}{2} R_s \\int_C |{J_s}|^2 dl.</math>\n\nIt can be shown that in a classical rectangular waveguide, the attenuation of the dominant mode <math>\\text{TE}_{10}</math> due to conduction currents is given, in [[Neper|Nepers]] per [[Metre|meter]], by<math display=\"block\" id=\"alpha_c_expression\">\\alpha_C = \\frac{R_s}{a^3 b \\beta k \\eta}  \\left( 2 b \\pi^2 + a^3 k^2 \\right) =  \\frac{R_s}{\\beta k \\eta} \\left( \\frac{2 \\pi^2}{a^3 } + \\frac{k^2}{b} \\right)</math>where\n\n* <math>a</math> is the width of the waveguide\n* <math>b</math> its height\n* <math>\\eta = \\sqrt{\\mu / \\epsilon}</math> the [[wave impedance]] \n* <math>k = \\omega \\sqrt{\\mu \\epsilon}</math> the [[wave vector]]\n* <math>\\delta = 1 / \\sqrt{\\pi f \\mu \\sigma}</math> the [[Skin Depth|skin depth]] in the conductor \n* <math>R_s = \\frac{1}{\\delta \\sigma} = \\sqrt{\\frac{\\omega \\mu}{2 \\sigma}}</math> is the [[sheet resistance]] (of surface impedance).\n\nIt is noticeable that <math>\\alpha_C</math> is directly linked to the substrate thickness <math>b</math>: the thinner the substrate, the higher the conduction losses. This can be explained keeping in mind that this ohmic losses are determined by integrating the current density on a path enclosing the waveguide walls. \n\nOn the top and bottom horizontal metallic plates, the current is scaled with <math>1/b</math>, due to the modification of the field intensity on these plates: when <math>b</math> increases, the field intensity decreases as well as the currents. In the vertical walls, this variation of <math>J_s^2</math> is compensated by the lengthening of the integration path <math>C</math>. As a result, the contribution of the vertical vias to the conductor losses is unchanged with <math>b</math>.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite journal|last=Bozzi|first=M.|last2=Perregrini|first2=L.|last3=Ke Wu|date=2008|title=Modeling of Conductor, Dielectric, and Radiation Losses in Substrate Integrated Waveguide by the Boundary Integral-Resonant Mode Expansion Method|url=http://ieeexplore.ieee.org/document/4682637/|journal=IEEE Transactions on Microwave Theory and Techniques|volume=56|issue=12|pages=3153\u20133161|doi=10.1109/TMTT.2008.2007140|issn=0018-9480}}</ref> That is the reason why there is two terms in the expression of <math>\\alpha_C</math>: the first is independent of <math>b</math> while the second one varies with <math>1/b</math>.\n\nAnother key point of the conduction losses experienced by the SIWs is linked to the [[Surface roughness|roughness]] of the surfaces that may appear due to the synthesis processes. This roughness decreases the effective conductivity of the metallic walls and subsequently increases the losses. This observation is of crucial importance for the design of SIWs as they are integrated on very thin substrates. In this case, the contribution of the conduction losses on the global attenuation is predominant.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lomakin|first=Konstantin|last2=Gold|first2=Gerald|last3=Helmreich|first3=Klaus|date=2018|title=Analytical Waveguide Model Precisely Predicting Loss and Delay Including Surface Roughness|url=https://ieeexplore.ieee.org/document/8356729/|journal=IEEE Transactions on Microwave Theory and Techniques|volume=66|issue=6|pages=2649\u20132662|doi=10.1109/TMTT.2018.2827383|issn=0018-9480}}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite thesis|title=Nanowire-based microwave devices in substrate integrated waveguide topology using a laser-assisted fabrication process|url=https://dial.uclouvain.be/pr/boreal/object/boreal:222909|publisher=UCL - Universit\u00e9 Catholique de Louvain|date=2019|language=en|first=Vivien|last=Van Kerckhoven}}</ref>\n\n=== Attenuation due to dielectric substrate ===\nThe attenuation due the [[dielectric]] behavior of the filling medium can be determined directly from the [[propagation constant]].<ref name=\":3\" /> Indeed, it can be proven that, making use of a [[Taylor expansion]] of the function <math display=\"inline\">\\sqrt{a^2 + x^2}</math> for <math display=\"inline\">x \\ll a</math>, the propagation constant is<math display=\"block\" id=\"alpha_c_expression\">\\gamma = \\alpha_D + j \\beta \\simeq \\frac{k^2 \\tan{\\delta}}{2 \\beta} + j\\beta</math>where <math>\\tan \\delta</math> is the [[loss tangent]] of the dielectric substrate. This approximation is correct if <math display=\"inline\">\\tan{\\delta} \\ll 1</math> which is usually the case in microwave electronics. At 10 GHz, <math display=\"inline\" id=\"alpha_c_expression\">\\tan{\\delta} = 0</math> in air, <math>1.5 \\times 10^{-4}</math> in Teflon and <math>1 \\times 10^{-4}</math>1 in bulk alumina. Then, the following identification can be made:<math display=\"block\" id=\"alpha_c_expression\">\\alpha_D = \\frac{k^2 \\tan{\\delta}}{2 \\beta}.</math>This relation is correct for both electrical and magnetic transverse modes.\n\n\nThe dielectric losses <math display=\"inline\" id=\"alpha_c_expression\">\\alpha_D</math> depend only on the substrate and not on the geometry: unlike the conduction losses, <math display=\"inline\" id=\"alpha_c_expression\">\\alpha_D</math> is not influenced by the substrate thickness. It transpires that the only way to reduce <math display=\"inline\" id=\"alpha_c_expression\">\\alpha_D</math> consists in choosing a template with better dielectric properties: the lower the loss tangent <math display=\"inline\" id=\"alpha_c_expression\">\\tan{\\delta}</math>, the lower the attenuation. \n\n=== Attenuation due to radiation ===\nBecause the vertical walls of the SIW are not continuous, radiation leakages may flow between the vias. These leakages can significantly affect the global transmission quality if the vias geometry is not chosen carefully. Some studies have been conducted to describe, predict and reduce the radiation losses. They have resulted in some simple geometric rules that have to be satisfied in order to reduce the radiation losses. <ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":7\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bozzi|first=Maurizio|last2=Pasian|first2=Marco|last3=Perregrini|first3=Luca|last4=Wu|first4=Ke|date=2009-10|title=On the losses in substrate-integrated waveguides and cavities|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/product/identifier/S1759078709990493/type/journal_article|journal=International Journal of Microwave and Wireless Technologies|language=en|volume=1|issue=5|pages=395\u2013401|doi=10.1017/S1759078709990493|issn=1759-0787}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Che|first=Wenquan|last2=Wang|first2=Dapeng|last3=Deng|first3=Kuan|last4=Chow|first4=Y. L.|date=2007-10|title=Leakage and ohmic losses investigation in substrate-integrated waveguide: SUBSTRATE-INTEGRATED WAVEGUIDE|url=http://doi.wiley.com/10.1029/2007RS003621|journal=Radio Science|language=en|volume=42|issue=5|pages=n/a\u2013n/a|doi=10.1029/2007RS003621}}</ref>\n\nThe geometric parameters of interest are the diameter <math display=\"inline\">d</math>, the spacing <math>s</math> and the center-to-center distance between the vias <math>a</math>. They must be tuned in such a way to approximate the behavior of a continuous metallic wall: the spacing of the vias has to remain small compared to their diameter, while the diameter must be small compared to the waveguide width (or waveguide wavelength). To keep the radiation losses reasonably small, the recommended values are<math display=\"block\">s \\leq 2 d ~~~~~~ \\textrm{and} ~~~~~~ d \\leq \\frac{a}{5}.</math>For a specific traveling mode, the leakages decrease with the increasing frequency and are maximal at the cut-off frequency of the mode. The radiation leakage factor <math>\\alpha_R</math> is independent of the substrate properties and independent of the height of the guide.\n\n==See also==\n* {{section link|Planar transmission line|Substrate integrated waveguide}}, also\n** {{section link|Planar transmission line|Transitions}}\n** {{section link|Planar transmission line|Circuit gallery}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.microwaves101.com/encyclopedias/substrate-integrated-waveguide Substrate Integrated Waveguide], at microwave101.com\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Substrate_Integrated_Waveguide}}\n[[Category:Planar transmission lines]]\n[[Category:Electronic design]]\n[[Category:Microwave technology]]\n[[Category:Electronics manufacturing]]\n", "name_user": "VK Vivien", "label": "safe", "comment": "equation layout correction", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Substrate_integrated_waveguide"}
{"title_page": "Dawat-e-Islami", "text_new": "{{Infobox Religious group|\n|group = Dawat-e-Islami<br/>{{Nastaliq|\u062f\u0639\u0648\u062a \u0627\u0633\u0644\u0627\u0645\u06cc}} \n|image = dawateislami logo.png\n|image_caption =  \n|affiliated members = 30 to 40 million<ref>{{cite web |last=Yousaf |first=Kamran |url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/250572/clamping-down-dawat-e-islami-comes-under-militarys-radar/ |title=Dawat-e-Islami comes under military\u2019s radar - The Express Tribune |publisher=Tribune.com.pk |accessdate=2015-09-20 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106002807/http://tribune.com.pk/story/250572/clamping-down-dawat-e-islami-comes-under-militarys-radar/ |archivedate=2015-11-06 }}</ref>\n|founder = [[Muhammad Ilyas Qadri]]<ref name=\"global encyclopaedia\">{{cite book | title=global encyclopaedia of islamic mystics and mysticism | publisher=Global Vision Publishing House, India | author=N. K. Singh | year=2015 | location=India | page=270 | isbn=978-81-8220-673-1}}</ref>\n|main leader = [[Muhammad Ilyas Qadri]]<ref name=\"Dawat E Islami\">{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BklRBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA178&dq=ilyas+qadri&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CCYQ6AEwA2oVChMI2ZmkzbjNxwIVIzLbCh3e5w2D#v=onepage&q=ilyas%20qadri&f=false | title=Karachi: Ordered Disorder and the Struggle for the City | publisher=Oxford University Press, Pakistan | author=Laurent Gayer | year=2014 | location=karachi | page=340 | isbn=978-0-19-935444-3}}</ref>\n|rels = [[Islam]]\n|scrips = [[Quran]], [[Hadith]], [[Sunnat]]\n|langs = Liturgical: [[Arabic language|Arabic]]<br/>In Bangladesh: [[Bengali language|Bengali]]<br/>In India & Pakistan:[[Urdu]]<br/>In the diaspora: In UK: Respective regional languages\n|website=[http://www.dawateislami.net Dawateislami.net] |TV Channel=Madni Channel}}\n\n'''Dawat-e-Islami''' is a global [[Barelvi]] Islam missionary movement based in [[Pakistan]]. It is working to convey the message of Quran and Sunnah.\n\nArshad al-Qadri, Shah Ahmed Noorani, Ahmad Saeed Kazmi and other elders raised their need for an Ahl-e-Sunnat propaganda movement at a meeting of Shah Ahmed Noorani's residence in Karachi in 1981. There were also Mufti dignitaries who were assigned to this task. He suggested the name of his disciple [[Muhammad Ilyas Qadri]], who was already doing so. Now they are continuing this mission.\nDawat-e-Islami was founded in Karachi in 1981 by Muhammad Ilyas Qadiri. Under his guidance, Dawat-e-Islami soon emerged as a global, peaceful and non-political movement of the [[Quran]] and [[Sunnah]] and is currently serving [[Islam]] in more than 105 different departments.\n\n\n==History==\nDawat-e-Islami was founded in Karachi in 1981 by [[Muhammad Ilyas Qadri|Muhammad Ilyas Attar]].\n\n[[File:Mosque And Education Center Run By Dawat-e-Islami.jpg|thumb|200x200px|Faizan-e-Madinah in Karachi]]In addition to [[Jamia]]ts, Dawat-e-Islami has also started an Islamic Schooling system as [[Dar-ul-Madinah]], that has set an objective of improving conventional academic studies in conformity with [[Sharia|Shari\u2019ah]]. It is one of over 102 departments functioning under Dawat-e-Islami, School is an International Schooling system being operated in different countries.<ref>[http://www.darulmadinah.net/introduction-2/ Dar-ul-Madinah] Retrieved 11 December 2018</ref>\n\nDawat-e-Islami has expanded to the United Kingdom, around 1995 holding its first Ijtima (weekly congregation) in [[Halifax, West Yorkshire|Halifax]]. As of December 2019, it now has at least 38 properties in the United Kingdom which are used as a network of [[Mosque|Masajid]], Islamic centers, schools and/or Jamias in order to create future scholars and good Human beings for the society. Some buildings have been completed and others are being worked upon. more than 100 thousand [[British Muslims]] are in some form or the other associated with Dawat-e-Islami in [[United Kingdom|UK]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6XCRmgig69MC&pg=PA37&dq=europe+dawat+e+islami&hl=en&sa=X&ei=aaZBUd6fJIG0rAe19ICgAw&ved=0CDEQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=europe%20dawat%20e%20islami&f=false |title=Global Encyclopaedia of Education (4 Vols. Set) - Rama Sankar Yadav & B.N. Mandal - Google Books |publisher=GoogleBooks|date=2007-01-01 |accessdate=11 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.duedil.com/company/05441337/dawat-e-islami-uk |title=Dawat-E-Islami UK |publisher=DueDil |accessdate=11 December 2018|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106002815/https://www.duedil.com/company/05441337/dawat-e-islami-uk |archivedate=2015-11-06 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mosquedirectory.co.uk/mosques/england/west-yorkshire/bradford/barkerend/Al-Amin-Mosque-Barkerend-Bradford-Bradford-West-Yorkshire/19 |title=Al Amin Mosque (Barkerend, Bradford, Bradford, West Yorkshire) Also Known as \"Faizan-e-Madina, Dawat e Islami UK Movement, Da'watul Islam UK & Eire, Uleman Council of Da'watul Islam\" |publisher=mosquedirectory.co.uk |accessdate=11 December 2018|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106002824/http://www.mosquedirectory.co.uk/mosques/england/west-yorkshire/bradford/barkerend/Al-Amin-Mosque-Barkerend-Bradford-Bradford-West-Yorkshire/19 |archivedate=2015-11-06 }}</ref>\n\nDawat-e-Islami operates twelve centers in [[Greece]] and seven in [[Spain]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.zmo.de/Mitarbeiter/Gugler/Jihad,%20Dawa%20and%20Hijra.pdf |format=PDF |title=Jihad, Da\u00b4wa, and Hijra: Islamic Missionary Movements in Europe |publisher=Zmo.de |accessdate=11 December 2018|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106002830/https://www.zmo.de/Mitarbeiter/Gugler/Jihad%2C%20Dawa%20and%20Hijra.pdf |archivedate=2015-11-06 }}\n</ref> \nIn 2009, a [[Madrassa]] was opened in [[Rotherham]], [[England]], for the education of young children and adults. \nIn [[Athens]], it has association with local [[Sufis]] and has established four centers.<ref name=\"BlanesMapril2013\">{{cite book|author1=Ruy Blanes|author2=Jos\u00e9 Mapril|title=Sites and Politics of Religious Diversity in Southern Europe: The Best of All Gods|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8accAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA169|date=11 July 2013|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-04-25524-1|pages=169\u2013 |accessdate=11 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nDawat-e-Islami [[United States|USA]] has centers in [[Chicago]], [[Texas]] and [[California]].\n\nDawat-e-Islami is also prominent in [[Africa]] with established centers in [[Kenya]], [[Tanzania]], [[Uganda]], [[South Africa]], and [[Madagascar]] are just a few among many countries in [[Africa]].\n \nIn [[Bangladesh]], Dawat-e-Islami led [[Jamia-tul-Madina]] has produced scholars who are serving in [[United Kingdom]].<ref name=\"EspositoVoll2007\">{{cite book|author1=John L. Esposito|author2=John Voll|author3=Osman Bakar|title=Asian Islam in the 21st Century|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9-8HrM55XfgC&pg=PA59|date=12 November 2007|publisher=Oxford University Press, USA|isbn=978-0-19-804421-5|pages=59\u2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170226132615/https://books.google.com/books?id=9-8HrM55XfgC&pg=PA59|archivedate=26 February 2017|accessdate=11 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Activities==\nThe two most significant activities of Dawat-e-Islami are Madani Qafila (missionary travel) and Madani Inamaat (self assessment questionnaires). It likes the followers to travel for specific days to spread the message of Islam to the people. Its leadership hardly interacts with the mainstream media, though the organization own its own TV Channel known as Madani Channel. It also arranges an annual gathering of its followers in [[Multan|Bangladesh]].<ref name=Dawn/>\n\nIn October 2002, a major Pakistani English-language newspaper reported about a 3-day public gathering in the city of [[Multan]], Pakistan which was held by Dawat-e-Isalmi organization and was attended by hundred thousands of people from all parts of Pakistan and other counteries. [[Pakistan Railways]] had used special trains from [[Karachi]], [[Hyderabad]] and [[Nawabshah]] to take passengers to Multan. [[Muhammad Ilyas Qadri]], chief of Dawat-e-Islami at the first and last sessions of the gathering.<ref name=Dawn>[https://www.dawn.com/news/62787/da-awat-moot-concludes Da'awat moot concludes [Dawat-e-Islami article on Dawn (newspaper)] Published 21 October 2002, Retrieved 9 December 2018</ref>\n\n===Call to Righteousness===\nDawat-e-Islami is organized in small units of lay preachers, who invite for weekly and annual congregations. They stress the strict and literal imitation of the life of [[Muhammad|Muhammed]] in all aspects of the daily routine. As missionary, the lay preacher has to act like an ideal [[Muslims|Muslim]]. The \"Islamic Project\" of Dawat-e-Islami is the \"Sunnaization\", that is the Re-shaping and Re-construction of the daily routine and the individual markers of identity based on the examples of the [[Muhammad|Prophet]] and the Sahabi as portrayed in the Hadith-Literature.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://crossasia-repository.ub.uni-heidelberg.de/142/ |title=Parrots of Paradise - Symbols of the Super-Muslim: Sunnah, Sunnaization and Self-Fashioning in the Islamic Missionary Movements Tablighi Jama'at, Da'wat-e Islami and Sunni Da'wat-e Islami |publisher=xasia Repository (Germany)|date=2008-07-31 |accessdate=10 December 2018|url-status= |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160201154221/http://crossasia-repository.ub.uni-heidelberg.de/142/ |archivedate=2016-02-01 }}</ref>\nIt arranges Haftawar Ijtima (weekly gatherings on every Thursday) in cities around the world.<ref name=Dawn/>\n\nDawat-e-Islami held its first congregation for deaf, dumb and blind students at its central headquarters Faizan-e-Madinah. Hundreds of students between 16 and 18 years of age attended the programme.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2007\\12\\10\\story_10-12-2007_pg7_25|title=Spreading the word|publisher=Daily Times (newspaper)|accessdate=10 December 2018|url-status= |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121103104135/http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2007%5C12%5C10%5Cstory_10-12-2007_pg7_25 |archivedate=November 3, 2012}}</ref> and now this department has grown globally with thousands of associates.\n\n[[File:Muhammad Hafeez, Misbah-ul-Haq, Kamran Akmal with Muballigh-e-Dawateislami.jpg|250px|thumb|right|[[Mohammad Hafeez]], [[Misbah-ul-Haq]], [[Kamran Akmal]] with Volunteers of Dawat-e-Islami]]\n\n===Annual Islamic gatherings (Ijtema)===\nIt annually organized a large congregation in [[Multan|Multan, Pakistan till 2008 which was discontinued keeping in view law and order situations in Pakistan for the safety of people]], for South Asia and in [[Birmingham]] for Europe.<ref name=\"crossasia-repository.ub.uni-heidelberg.de\">{{cite web|url=http://crossasia-repository.ub.uni-heidelberg.de/142/1/Gugler_Politics_of_Difference.pdf|title=The Politics of Difference|publisher=Crossasia.repository.ub.uni-heidelberg.de|format=PDF|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150928185952/http://crossasia-repository.ub.uni-heidelberg.de/142/1/Gugler_Politics_of_Difference.pdf|archivedate=2015-09-28|url-status=live|accessdate=11 December 2018}}Jihad, Da\u00b4wa, and Hijra: Islamic Missionary Movements in Europe \n</ref>\nIn 2002, an estimated half-a-million people participated in its congregation at [[Multan]], Pakistan.<ref name=Dawn/> The 2009 event was canceled because of security concerns. every year millions of people attend the annual congregation held in [[Dhaka]], [[Bangladesh]].\n\n=== Madarsa-tul Madina (Religious Basic Education System) ===\nIn Madrasa tul Madina, children are taught how to read the [[Quran|Qur\u2019an]] in Arabic, as well as foundational Islamic studies. Many{{vague|date=April 2019}} children memorize the entire Quran under the guidance of this department. Currently, Madrasa tul Madina has around 3790 branches, with approximately 169,000 boys and girls studying free of charge in these institutions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2006%5C10%5C30%5Cstory_30-10-2006_pg7_15|title=Dawat-e-Islami beats KKF (Khidmat-e-Khalq Foundation) in zakat collection|publisher=Daily Times (newspaper)|accessdate=10 December 2018 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606161257/http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2006%5C10%5C30%5Cstory_30-10-2006_pg7_15 |archivedate=June 6, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Jamia-tul-Madina]]\n*[[Faizan e Sunnat]]\n*[[Muhammad Ilyas Qadri]]\n*[[Ahmed Raza Khan Barelvi]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==Notes==\n*{{cite book |title=Dawat-e-Islami ka Maqsad : Mujay Apni Aur Sari Dunya Kay Logo Ki Islah Ki Koshish Karni Hay  \u0627\u0646 \u0634\u0627\u0621 \u0627\u0644\u0644\u06c1 \u0639\u0632\u0648\u062c\u0644 |last=Attar Qadri |first=Ilyas |publisher=Maktaba Ahle Sunnah Karachi|year=1991}}\n*{{cite book |title=Mission Medina: Da'wat-e Islami und Tabligi Gama'at|last=Gugler |first=Thomas K. |publisher=W\u00fcrzburg: Ergon|year=2011}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Dawat-e-Islami}}\n*[https://www.dawateislami.net Dawat-e-Islami Official Website]\n*\n*[http://risingsunoverport.co.za/46973/fire-engulfs-overport-mosque/ The Dawat-E-Islami Mosque on Kenilworth Road]\n*[https://www.thenewstribe.com/2012/11/02/saeed-ajmals-chautha-now-in-love-with-dawat-e-islami/ Saeed Ajmal: Now in love with Dawat-e-Islami]\n\n{{Dawat E Islami|Key Personalities=Maulana Ilyas Attar Qadri, Muhammad Imran Attari}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dawat-e-Islami}}\n[[Category:Dawat-e-Islami]]\n[[Category:1981 establishments in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Ahmed Raza Khan Barelvi]]\n[[Category:Islam in Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Islam in North America]]\n[[Category:Islam in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Islam in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Islamic organizations established in 1980]]\n[[Category:Sunni organizations]]\n[[Category:Sufi organizations]]\n[[Category:Islamic organisations based in Pakistan]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Religious group|\n|group = Dawat-e-Islami<br/>{{Nastaliq|\u062f\u0639\u0648\u062a \u0627\u0633\u0644\u0627\u0645\u06cc}} \n|image = dawateislami logo.png\n|image_caption =  \n|affiliated members = 30 to 40 million<ref>{{cite web |last=Yousaf |first=Kamran |url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/250572/clamping-down-dawat-e-islami-comes-under-militarys-radar/ |title=Dawat-e-Islami comes under military\u2019s radar - The Express Tribune |publisher=Tribune.com.pk |accessdate=2015-09-20 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106002807/http://tribune.com.pk/story/250572/clamping-down-dawat-e-islami-comes-under-militarys-radar/ |archivedate=2015-11-06 }}</ref>\n|founder = [[Muhammad Ilyas Qadri]]<ref name=\"global encyclopaedia\">{{cite book | title=global encyclopaedia of islamic mystics and mysticism | publisher=Global Vision Publishing House, India | author=N. K. Singh | year=2015 | location=India | page=270 | isbn=978-81-8220-673-1}}</ref>\n|main leader = [[Muhammad Ilyas Qadri]]<ref name=\"Dawat E Islami\">{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BklRBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA178&dq=ilyas+qadri&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CCYQ6AEwA2oVChMI2ZmkzbjNxwIVIzLbCh3e5w2D#v=onepage&q=ilyas%20qadri&f=false | title=Karachi: Ordered Disorder and the Struggle for the City | publisher=Oxford University Press, Pakistan | author=Laurent Gayer | year=2014 | location=karachi | page=340 | isbn=978-0-19-935444-3}}</ref>\n|rels = [[Islam]]\n|scrips = [[Quran]], [[Hadith]], [[Sunnat]]\n|langs = Liturgical: [[Arabic language|Arabic]]<br/>In Bangladesh: [[Bengali language|Bengali]]<br/>In India & Pakistan:[[Urdu]]<br/>In the diaspora: In UK: Respective regional languages\n|website=[http://www.dawateislami.net Dawateislami.net] |TV Channel=Madni Channel}}\n\n'''Dawat-e-Islami''' is a global [[Barelvi]] Islam missionary movement based in [[Pakistan]]. It is working to convey the message of Quran and Sunnah.\n\nArshad al-Qadri, Shah Ahmed Noorani, Ahmad Saeed Kazmi and other elders raised their need for an Ahl-e-Sunnat propaganda movement at a meeting of Shah Ahmed Noorani's residence in Karachi in 1981. There were also Mufti dignitaries who were assigned to this task. He suggested the name of his disciple [[Muhammad Ilyas Qadri]], who was already doing so. Now they are continuing this mission.\nDawat-e-Islami was founded in Karachi in 1981 by Muhammad Ilyas Qadiri. Under his guidance, Dawat-e-Islami soon emerged as a global, peaceful and non-political movement of the [[Quran]] and [[Sunnah]] and is currently serving [[Islam]] in more than 105 different departments.\n\n\n==History==\nDawat-e-Islami was founded in Karachi in 1981 by [[Muhammad Ilyas Qadri|Muhammad Ilyas Attar]].\n\n[[File:Mosque And Education Center Run By Dawat-e-Islami.jpg|thumb|200x200px|Faizan-e-Madinah in Karachi]]In addition to [[Jamia]]ts, Dawat-e-Islami has also started an Islamic Schooling system as [[Dar-ul-Madinah]], that has set an objective of improving conventional academic studies in conformity with [[Sharia|Shari\u2019ah]]. It is one of over 102 departments functioning under Dawat-e-Islami, School is an International Schooling system being operated in different countries.<ref>[http://www.darulmadinah.net/introduction-2/ Dar-ul-Madinah] Retrieved 11 December 2018</ref>\n\nDawat-e-Islami has expanded to the United Kingdom, around 1995 holding its first Ijtima (weekly congregation) in [[Halifax, West Yorkshire|Halifax]]. As of December 2019, it now has at least 38 properties in the United Kingdom which are used as a network of [[Mosque|Masajid]], Islamic centers, schools and/or Jamias in order to create future scholars and good Human beings for the society. Some buildings have been completed and others are being worked upon. more than 100 thousand [[British Muslims]] are in some form or the other associated with Dawat-e-Islami in [[United Kingdom|UK]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6XCRmgig69MC&pg=PA37&dq=europe+dawat+e+islami&hl=en&sa=X&ei=aaZBUd6fJIG0rAe19ICgAw&ved=0CDEQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=europe%20dawat%20e%20islami&f=false |title=Global Encyclopaedia of Education (4 Vols. Set) - Rama Sankar Yadav & B.N. Mandal - Google Books |publisher=GoogleBooks|date=2007-01-01 |accessdate=11 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.duedil.com/company/05441337/dawat-e-islami-uk |title=Dawat-E-Islami UK |publisher=DueDil |accessdate=11 December 2018|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106002815/https://www.duedil.com/company/05441337/dawat-e-islami-uk |archivedate=2015-11-06 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mosquedirectory.co.uk/mosques/england/west-yorkshire/bradford/barkerend/Al-Amin-Mosque-Barkerend-Bradford-Bradford-West-Yorkshire/19 |title=Al Amin Mosque (Barkerend, Bradford, Bradford, West Yorkshire) Also Known as \"Faizan-e-Madina, Dawat e Islami UK Movement, Da'watul Islam UK & Eire, Uleman Council of Da'watul Islam\" |publisher=mosquedirectory.co.uk |accessdate=11 December 2018|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106002824/http://www.mosquedirectory.co.uk/mosques/england/west-yorkshire/bradford/barkerend/Al-Amin-Mosque-Barkerend-Bradford-Bradford-West-Yorkshire/19 |archivedate=2015-11-06 }}</ref>\n\nDawat-e-Islami operates twelve centers in [[Greece]] and seven in [[Spain]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.zmo.de/Mitarbeiter/Gugler/Jihad,%20Dawa%20and%20Hijra.pdf |format=PDF |title=Jihad, Da\u00b4wa, and Hijra: Islamic Missionary Movements in Europe |publisher=Zmo.de |accessdate=11 December 2018|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106002830/https://www.zmo.de/Mitarbeiter/Gugler/Jihad%2C%20Dawa%20and%20Hijra.pdf |archivedate=2015-11-06 }}\n</ref> \nIn 2009, a [[Madrassa]] was opened in [[Rotherham]], [[England]], for the education of young children and adults. \nIn [[Athens]], it has association with local [[Sufis]] and has established four centers.<ref name=\"BlanesMapril2013\">{{cite book|author1=Ruy Blanes|author2=Jos\u00e9 Mapril|title=Sites and Politics of Religious Diversity in Southern Europe: The Best of All Gods|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8accAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA169|date=11 July 2013|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-04-25524-1|pages=169\u2013 |accessdate=11 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nDawat-e-Islami [[United States|USA]] has centers in [[Chicago]], [[Texas]] and [[California]].\n\nDawat-e-Islami is also prominent in [[Africa]] with established centers in [[Kenya]], [[Tanzania]], [[Uganda]], [[South Africa]], and [[Madagascar]] are just a few among many countries in [[Africa]].\n \nIn [[Bangladesh]], Dawat-e-Islami led [[Jamia-tul-Madina]] has produced scholars who are serving in [[United Kingdom]].<ref name=\"EspositoVoll2007\">{{cite book|author1=John L. Esposito|author2=John Voll|author3=Osman Bakar|title=Asian Islam in the 21st Century|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9-8HrM55XfgC&pg=PA59|date=12 November 2007|publisher=Oxford University Press, USA|isbn=978-0-19-804421-5|pages=59\u2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170226132615/https://books.google.com/books?id=9-8HrM55XfgC&pg=PA59|archivedate=26 February 2017|accessdate=11 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Activities==\nThe two most significant activities of Dawat-e-Islami are Madani Qafila (missionary travel) and Madani Inamaat (self assessment questionnaires). It likes the followers to travel for specific days to spread the message of Islam to the people. Its leadership hardly interacts with the mainstream media, though the organization own its own TV Channel known as Madani Channel. It also arranges an annual gathering of its followers in [[Multan|Bangladesh]].<ref name=Dawn/>\n\nIn October 2002, a major Pakistani English-language newspaper reported about a 3-day public gathering in the city of [[Multan]], Pakistan which was held by Dawat-e-Isalmi organization and was attended by hundred thousands of people from all parts of Pakistan and other counteries. [[Pakistan Railways]] had used special trains from [[Karachi]], [[Hyderabad]] and [[Nawabshah]] to take passengers to Multan. [[Muhammad Ilyas Qadri]], chief of Dawat-e-Islami at the first and last sessions of the gathering.<ref name=Dawn>[https://www.dawn.com/news/62787/da-awat-moot-concludes Da'awat moot concludes [Dawat-e-Islami article on Dawn (newspaper)] Published 21 October 2002, Retrieved 9 December 2018</ref>\n\n===Call to Righteousness===\nDawat-e-Islami is organized in small units of lay preachers, who invite for weekly and annual congregations. They stress the strict and literal imitation of the life of [[Muhammad|Muhammed]] in all aspects of the daily routine. As missionary, the lay preacher has to act like an ideal [[Muslims|Muslim]]. The \"Islamic Project\" of Dawat-e-Islami is the \"Sunnaization\", that is the Re-shaping and Re-construction of the daily routine and the individual markers of identity based on the examples of the [[Muhammad|Prophet]] and the Sahabi as portrayed in the Hadith-Literature.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://crossasia-repository.ub.uni-heidelberg.de/142/ |title=Parrots of Paradise - Symbols of the Super-Muslim: Sunnah, Sunnaization and Self-Fashioning in the Islamic Missionary Movements Tablighi Jama'at, Da'wat-e Islami and Sunni Da'wat-e Islami |publisher=xasia Repository (Germany)|date=2008-07-31 |accessdate=10 December 2018|url-status= |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160201154221/http://crossasia-repository.ub.uni-heidelberg.de/142/ |archivedate=2016-02-01 }}</ref>\nIt arranges Haftawar Ijtima (weekly gatherings on every Thursday) in cities around the world.<ref name=Dawn/>\n\nDawat-e-Islami held its first congregation for deaf, dumb and blind students at its central headquarters Faizan-e-Madinah. Hundreds of students between 16 and 18 years of age attended the programme.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2007\\12\\10\\story_10-12-2007_pg7_25|title=Spreading the word|publisher=Daily Times (newspaper)|accessdate=10 December 2018|url-status= |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121103104135/http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2007%5C12%5C10%5Cstory_10-12-2007_pg7_25 |archivedate=November 3, 2012}}</ref> and now this department has grown globally with thousands of associates.\n\n[[File:Muhammad Hafeez, Misbah-ul-Haq, Kamran Akmal with Muballigh-e-Dawateislami.jpg|250px|thumb|right|[[Mohammad Hafeez]], [[Misbah-ul-Haq]], [[Kamran Akmal]] with Volunteers of Dawat-e-Islami]]\n\n===Annual Islamic gatherings (Ijtema)===\nIt annually organized a large congregation in [[Multan|Multan, Pakistan till 2008 which was discontinued keeping in view law and order situations in Pakistan for the safety of people]], for South Asia and in [[Birmingham]] for Europe.<ref name=\"crossasia-repository.ub.uni-heidelberg.de\">{{cite web|url=http://crossasia-repository.ub.uni-heidelberg.de/142/1/Gugler_Politics_of_Difference.pdf|title=The Politics of Difference|publisher=Crossasia.repository.ub.uni-heidelberg.de|format=PDF|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150928185952/http://crossasia-repository.ub.uni-heidelberg.de/142/1/Gugler_Politics_of_Difference.pdf|archivedate=2015-09-28|url-status=live|accessdate=11 December 2018}}Jihad, Da\u00b4wa, and Hijra: Islamic Missionary Movements in Europe \n</ref>\nIn 2002, an estimated half-a-million people participated in its congregation at [[Multan]], Pakistan.<ref name=Dawn/> The 2009 event was canceled because of security concerns. every year millions of people attend the annual congregation held in [[Dhaka]], [[Bangladesh]].\n\n=== Madarsa-tul Madina (Religious Basic Education System) ===\nIn Madrasa tul Madina, children are taught how to read the [[Quran|Qur\u2019an]] in Arabic, as well as foundational Islamic studies. Many{{vague|date=April 2019}} children memorize the entire Quran under the guidance of this department. Currently, Madrasa tul Madina has around 3790 branches, with approximately 169,000 boys and girls studying free of charge in these institutions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2006%5C10%5C30%5Cstory_30-10-2006_pg7_15|title=Dawat-e-Islami beats KKF (Khidmat-e-Khalq Foundation) in zakat collection|publisher=Daily Times (newspaper)|accessdate=10 December 2018 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606161257/http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2006%5C10%5C30%5Cstory_30-10-2006_pg7_15 |archivedate=June 6, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Jamia-tul-Madina]]\n*[[Faizan e Sunnat]]\n*[[Muhammad Ilyas Qadri]]\n*[[Ahmed Raza Khan Barelvi]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==Notes==\n*{{cite book |title=Dawat-e-Islami ka Maqsad : Mujay Apni Aur Sari Dunya Kay Logo Ki Islah Ki Koshish Karni Hay  \u0627\u0646 \u0634\u0627\u0621 \u0627\u0644\u0644\u06c1 \u0639\u0632\u0648\u062c\u0644 |last=Attar Qadri |first=Ilyas |publisher=Maktaba Ahle Sunnah Karachi|year=1991}}\n*{{cite book |title=Mission Medina: Da'wat-e Islami und Tabligi Gama'at|last=Gugler |first=Thomas K. |publisher=W\u00fcrzburg: Ergon|year=2011}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Dawat-e-Islami}}\n*[https://www.dawateislami.net Dawat-e-Islami Official Website]\n*\n*[http://risingsunoverport.co.za/46973/fire-engulfs-overport-mosque/ The Dawat-E-Islami Mosque on Kenilworth Road]\n*[https://www.thenewstribe.com/2012/11/02/saeed-ajmals-chautha-now-in-love-with-dawat-e-islami/ Saeed Ajmal: Now in love with Dawat-e-Islami]\n\n{{Dawat E Islami|Key Personalities=Maulana Ilyas Attar Qadri, Muhammad Imran Attari}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dawat-e-Islami}}\n[[Category:Dawat-e-Islami]]\n[[Category:1981 establishments in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Ahmed Raza Khan Barelvi]]\n[[Category:Islam in Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Islam in North America]]\n[[Category:Islam in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Islam in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Islamic organizations established 